You have dangling reference.

Class `OutputArray` has a constructor which takes `Mat` by reference:

    _OutputArray(Mat&amp; m);

When you create thread you pass `left` - as `Mat` instance. Becuase a signature of thread body takes `OutputArray` which can take `Mat` this `Mat` as argument is created as copy. Then `OutputArray` takes this temporary object by reference. When `thread` started executing, `OutputArray` refers to destroyed temp `Mat` instance (`thread` needs to store only `OutputArray`, no temporary `Mat`).

Solution? Just pass original `left` into `OutputArray`:

 	thread t1(testThread, OutputArray(left));
 	t1.join();
in above code no temporary instance of `Mat` as copy of `left` is created.

